[2]
Date: 16 Apr 2010
Source: Wesh.com [edited]
<http://www.wesh.com/health/23170550/detail.html>


Stray Cat Bites Prompt Rabies Alert
Homeowner, Driver Attacked In Volusia County
--------------------------------------------
The Volusia County Health Department has issued a rabies alert for
portions of 2 cities and part of the county after 2 unprovoked
attacks on people by feral cats.

A cat bit a driver and passenger in South Daytona on 9 Mar 2010,
after the motorist hit the cat and the 2 people tried to help the
animal. [In the case of an animal being hit by a vehicle, it is
natural to assess the condition of the animal, realizing the animal
may bite or scratch out of fear. That fear may not be associated with
rabies at that moment in time. - Mod.TG]

Another cat ran into a private home in Port Orange and attacked the
homeowner on 12 Apr 2010.

Both cats were euthanized and tested positive for rabies.

Officials encouraged the public not to feed or approach feral cats or
other wildlife.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Rabies is fatal to cats and dogs and owners should be encouraged to
vaccinate their pets, including horses and cattle. Rabies is usually
fatal to people. Exposed people need to seek medical attention for
post exposure prophylaxis. - Mod.TG]

